<TEXT>
the state agreed friday to pay a widow and 
her two children more than 19 million in the first settlement of 
a lawsuit stemming from the april 1987 collapse of a new york state 
thruway bridge 
ten people died when the fourlane bridge along the nations 
longest toll road collapsed into the floodswollen schoharie creek 
about 40 miles west of albany 
the claim settled friday was filed by the estate of robert 
hoffman a niagara mohawk worker killed when the car he was in 
plunged into the raging waters also suing were hoffmans widow 
karen and their two children scott hoffman 20 and tara hoffman 
18 the hoffmans live in rensselaer county 
the family had sued the state and the thruway authority for 
158 million 
under the order approved by court of claims judge louis benza 
the state agreed to immediately pay mrs hoffman 50000 and the 
thruway authority agreed to pay her 248000 
also the thruway authority agreed to structured payments to 
mrs hoffman and her children that over the next 25 years would 
total at least 167 million 
nancy connell a spokeswoman for state attorney general robert 
abrams said she expected other settlements to be reached soon on 
some of the lawsuits filed by survivors of the other nine victims 
the 559mile new york state thruway runs from near new york 
city north to albany and then west to the pennsylvania border 
south of buffalo 
