<TEXT>
new us visa regulations leave the door open 
for suspected nazi war criminals to enter the united states say 
officials who have intercepted about 12 of them trying to get into 
the country in recent months 
those caught were west germans took advantage of a program 
enacted last summer which allows residents of west germany to enter 
the united states without a visa 
previously west germans had to apply for visitor visas at a 
us consulate where their applications were checked against the 
thousands of names on a watchlist of suspected nazi war 
criminals 
under the program visitors are now screened when they reach a 
us airport or border crossing their passports are then checked 
against an immigration and naturalization service computer list of 
people ineligible to enter the united states 
but officials say some probably get through either because of 
inefficiency or work overload 
neal sher who heads the justice departments nazihunting 
office said he expects an increase in the number of interceptions 
as the summer tourist season begins 
he said the changed visa rules tie up his time with calls from 
various airports where inspectors have stopped people with names 
corresponding to those on the watchlist 
sher said a man who recently arrived at bostons logan airport 
on a saturday night after winning a free trip to the united 
states that included a cruise from florida was found to have been 
extradited to poland in 1947 from the us zone of west germany for 
suspected involvement in nazi atrocities 
we put him on a plane home the next morning sher said 
but with the dropped visa requirement the last line of 
defense has become the first sher said 
sher said some take a chance on slipping past passport control 
last saturday he said another west germans name popped up in 
the ins computer when he arrived at the airport in fort lauderdale 
fla 
sher said he went to his office and found the man had been a 
guard at a nazi death camp under questioning which sher directed 
by phone the man admitted he had an underarm tattoo of the elite 
nazi ss unit 
needless to say he never got to see florida either said 
sher 
although sher has complained to other government agencies 
involved in the program the state department said it was very 
satisfied with the visa waiver scheme 
the ins said some 121000 west germans entered the united states 
between july and december in 1989 only 46 west germans were 
refused entry among them about a dozen for suspected nazi activity 
the watchlist compiled by the justice department includes 
names of people ineligible to enter the country for various 
reasons including suspected criminal or terrorist activity 
people are placed on the list who are suspected of complicity 
with nazi war crimes but they are not necessarily considered 
indictable in the united states 
when the justice department has evidence about a watchlist 
suspect which it believes is sufficiently grave and irrefutable it 
informs west germany or other countries that may want to prosecute 
