<TEXT>
federal health officials say they will 
probably ease a policy that bars blood donations from all haitians 
and black africans who were considered at high risk for carrying 
the aids virus 
immigrants from haiti and from subsaharan africa say they are 
unfairly stigmatized by the ban which they claim has no scientific 
basis 
our blood is as safe as anybody elses blood alix mathieu 
a university of cincinnati medical school professor who is haitian 
told a food and drug administration advisory committee on friday 
the scientific facts are not very hard he said urging 
that we be considered as any other americans 
the panel of experts recommended the blooddonor exclusion be 
dropped and the fda instead develop screening questions and 
procedures to identify those haitians and black africans who are at 
high risk for aids 
dr paul parkman the fdas aids coordinator said the agency 
will likely make some changes in the policy but he noted that 
while three panel members approved the recommendation two others 
voted for a less drastic course 
were inclined to change the policy as long as the safety of 
the nations blood supply can be maintained parkman said but we 
need to think a little bit about what each of the committee 
members said 
the difficulty fda scientists say is the virus is spread among 
haitians and subsaharan africans chiefly through heterosexual 
contact they say it is more difficult to identify risk from 
heterosexual contact than risk from homosexual contact or 
needlesharing by intravenous drug users which is how the virus 
usually spreads among black hispanic and white americans 
but haitianamericans aids activists and the american red cross 
urged the agency to find some way to screen for high risk donors 
without stigmatizing whole segments of the population 
it is a racist behavior said brunir shakelton executive 
director of the cambridge american haitian association 
several dozen haitians attended the meeting at the fdas 
headquarters in nearby rockville md at the same time in new york 
50000 haitians and african americans protesting the ban rallied in 
lower manhattan closing the brooklyn bridge for more than two 
hours and tying up traffic around city hall 
all donated blood is tested for the aids virus before it is 
used but an infected person may not test positive for six months 
after they contracted the virus 
the ban has been in place in part since 1984 when haitians 
who had emigrated to the united states since 1977 were excluded 
from the list of eligible donors central africans were added in 
1986 and that was extended to include immigrants from subsaharan 
africa and nearby islands haitians and subsaharan africans who 
had emigrated before 1977 were added in february 
the panel voted after several dozen haitians told the fda 
committee they consider the ban discriminatory witnesses said the 
policy has cost haitians their jobs and homes 
parkman said he was inclined to allow haitians who came to the 
united states before 1977 to donate blood as scientific evidence 
indicates those who emigrated after that have most of the cases of 
aids 
for subsaharan africans he said he was inclined to allow them 
to donate blood if a blood bank has the ability to test donors for 
the hiv2 virus as well as the hiv1 
the hiv2 virus is a less common cause of aids there is 
currently no test in the united states for detecting the evidence 
of hiv2 but some tests are in development 
</TEXT>
