<TEXT>
the united states has joined 31 other 
american states in agreeing to step up the war on drugs with 
heavier penalties and improved international cooperation 
despite fridays accord the united states and mexico remained 
at odds over the reported abduction of a mexican doctor to face 
us charges in the killing of a drug agent 
mexico has threatened to stop cooperating with the united states 
in antidrug efforts if more suspects are kidnapped on its 
territory 
the 20point antidrug plan dubbed the declaration of ixtapa 
was signed by the united states mexico and 30 other members of the 
organization of american states or oas 
it calls for better education and prevention starting in grammar 
school greater coordination in police work improvements in 
information exchanges and tougher legislation 
it also calls for stronger measures against money laundering and 
the illegal sale of weapons and explosives it recommends stricter 
controls on lab equipment and chemicals for making drugs 
the declaration includes economic aid through international 
financial institutions led by the inter american development bank 
the program would help farmers substitute legal crops for 
highpaying illicit ones like coca leaf poppies and marijuana no 
figures were given for funding 
latin america is a leading grower and producer of cocaine 
heroin and marijuana the united states is the worlds leading 
consumer and center for money laundering 
experts from the oas nations unanimously concluded in a report 
to justice ministers at the fourday meeting that nowhere is the 
drug problem more serious and pressing than in this hemisphere 
the declaration also called for greater cooperation by 
governments for adequate control of their borders with 
absolute respect for the sovereingty and territorial integrity of 
states 
however the accord made no mention of extraditing suspects from 
one country to another especially to the united states 
extradition has been a touchy issue in latin america in recent 
years exacerbated recently by the alleged abduction of the suspect 
from mexico 
the mexican government has demanded an explanation for what an 
embassy spokesman in washington called the illegal detention of 
dr humberto alvarez machain 
according to news reports bounty hunters seized the 
gynecologist at his guadalajara office on april 2 for a large 
reward offered by the us drug enforcement administration 
alvarez machain was brought to el paso texas the next day and 
arrested 
the doctor is one of 19 mexicans indicted by a federal grand 
jury in los angeles on charges in the 1985 tortureslaying of dea 
agent enrique kiki camarena he is accused of drugging camarena 
while the agent was tortured by his killers 
us attorney general richard thornburgh issued a statement 
friday saying although the drug enforcement administration has 
not completed its investigation of the circumstances surrounding 
the apprehension of dr machain it has been confirmed that no dea 
personnel were present when he was taken into custody in mexico or 
when he was boarded onto an aircraft in that country 
justice department spokesman david runkel said he did not 
