<TEXT>
president bush is believed ready to sign a 
bill requiring the government to keep track of hate crimes 
against minorities but the sponsor says the program could be 
torpedoed by a budget squeeze at the fbi 
the implementation of the landmark hate crimes legislation 
will be severely hampered if the staff responsible for 
administering the law at the fbi is reduced rep charles 
schumer dny said 
schumer made his comment came friday after the fbi acknowledged 
that it is considering a proposal to discontinue its uniform crime 
report an annual count of crimes in america 
under the recently approved hate crimes bill the justice 
department is to keep statistics on offenses related to race 
religion sexual orientation and ethnicity as part of the uniform 
crime report 
approval of the hate crimes bill followed complaints about a 
wave of such offenses on the part of neonazi skinheads and other 
bigot groups a 1988 justice department report however said no 
such statistics were available 
the bush administration supported the measure which was 
sponsored in the house by schumer and the president was expected 
to sign it this week 
fbi officials however told schumer at a hearing thursday that 
a budget squeeze was draining manpower from their 
statisticsgathering staff 
they said a proposal that would in effect eliminate the 
60yearold crime reports was under consideration by the records 
management division as a way to help absorb the manpower cuts 
fbi officials said a longstanding drive by the office of 
management and budget to slash payroll and channel work to private 
contractors was responsible for much of the reduction in manpower 
they said the records division has lost 258 positions since 1987 
and plans call for elimination of 92 more the division has more 
than 1100 employees 
special agent j harper wilson in charge of the uniform crime 
reports said his staff might be spared the brunt of the cuts but 
would have to absorb at least 30 and more likely far more than that 
schumer issued a statement friday saying that at a time when 
information on overall crime is woefully thin the bush 
administration should be moving forcefully to bolster its 
understanding of crime not undermining it i hope the president 
personally intervenes to prevent these cutbacks 
without it his signing into law of the hate crimes measure 
would be little more than an empty gesture he added 
schumer also sent a letter to attorney general dick thornburgh 
saying that a large staff cut would eviscerate the bureaus 
ability to collect and distribute the uniform crime reports 
the justice department also maintains a separate datagathering 
arm the bureau of justice statistics 
