<TEXT>
lech walesa was reelected as chairman of 
solidarity by an overwhelming margin saturday winning a mandate to 
shape the unions future during the difficult transition from 
communism to capitalism 
in his victory speech walesa said the onceoutlawed union 
cannot rest on its laurels after removing the communists from 
power but must bear responsibility for the countrys future 
i am very happy but i am aware of what a cross a union cross 
a polish cross we are to bear walesa told delegates to 
solidaritys second national congress 
whats before us is even more difficult than what is behind us 
we shall not waste the heritage of generations he said 
delegates welcomed walesas victory over two challengers with 
chants of leszek leszek leszek a diminutive of his first 
name 
walesa the shipyard electrician who has led solidarity since 
its birth in 1980 received 775 percent of the vote the unions 
election commission said 
the delegates selecting a leader to shape the unions role in 
postcommunist poland cast 362 ballots for walesa 52 for veteran 
activist andrzej slowik and 25 for tomasz wojcik a littleknown 
local strike leader 
although walesa was widely expected to win he joked later that 
i was not that sure of the victory because i have done a lot of 
mischief during the 10 years as chairman 
the election took place on the third day of the congress which 
is meeting in a sports hall in this baltic port city the 
birthplace of solidarity during a nationwide strike wave in august 
1980 
the union held its last congress in the fall of 1981 just 
months before it was suppressed under martial law 
the sixday congress scheduled to end tuesday also will draw 
up a program determining solidaritys future role now that it has 
gone from being an opposition movement to being part of the 
political establishment 
walesas reelection comes as public opinion polls show the 
union losing popularity due to economic hardships brought by the 
solidarityled governments shock treatment austerity program for 
the countrys moribund economy 
some union members had criticized walesa for being undemocratic 
in his means of running solidarity but none of the bestknown 
union activists challenged him 
in order to ensure a choice walesa himself proposed the 
candidacy of slowik a bus driver and union leader from the central 
city of lodz who has often advocated a more militant course for the 
union slowik opposed any concessions to the communists during the 
negotiations that led to the relegalization of solidarity in april 
1989 after a sevenyear ban 
wojcik a chemist helped lead 1988 strikes against the 
thencommunist government in the wroclaw region in southwest poland 
in speeches before the balloting walesa and slowik differed 
over a key issue facing solidarity whether the union should step 
back from the political arena to emphasize its original trade union 
goals of defending workers interests 
walesa advocated an intermediate program mixing political 
and trade union goals but slowik said solidaritys only role 
should be as the leadership of a trade union not a social 
movement or political party 
the congress is expected to outline the unions stand on the 
governments economic reform program aimed at transforming polands 
centrally planned communist economy into a marketoriented 
capitalist system 
in its initial stages the reforms austerity measures have 
raised prices and thrown about 200000 people out of work 
solidaritybacked candidates swept partially free parliamentary 
elections last june and took control of the government from the 
communists installing tadeusz mazowiecki a former union adviser 
as prime minister in the east blocs first noncommunist government 
in almost 40 years 
but only about 22 million of the 10 million members the union 
claimed in 1981 have joined since it won back its legal status a 
year ago 
some critics have accused walesa of viewing the union 
chairmanship as only a stepping stone for an eventual bid for 
president of poland the post is currently held by gen wojciech 
jaruzelski the former communist party leader who led the december 
1981 martial law crackdown that suppressed solidarity 
earlier this month walesa raised the possibility of running for 
president but then backed away he said his remarks were meant 
only to spur the government to make the needed political and 
economic reforms 
