with a single explosive charge it would blow itself to pieces 
said phillip wright chief executive of sheffield forgemasters 
but experts say there are other ways to accelerate a projectile 
and some have pointed to the german v4 built in world war ii 
the v4 according to the imperial war museum was a 150mm gun 
built in 40 sections totaling 492 feet the v4 had 28 powder 
chambers that fired in rapid sequence as the projectile moved up 
the barrel 
built near calais on the french side of the english channel the 
v4 was bombed by the royal air force before it could fire any of 
its 150pound projectiles at london 
the independent citing unidentified sources in space resaerch 
said forgemasters built parts for two barrels each 492 feet long 
in 26 sections forgemasters has acknowledged shipping 44 pieces of 
tubing before the eight were seized 
