<TEXT>
space shuttle columbias flight 
next month to study the cosmos may be overshadowed by the hubble 
space telescopes historic journey aboard discovery but it will 
mark a first for glasnost 
columbias astronauts plan to talk via ham radio to two 
cosmonauts aboard the soviet space station mir its believed that 
will be the first time an american and soviet spacecraft have 
exchanged direct radio communication said ronald a parise a 
payload specialist who came up with the idea 
columbias commander vance brand said he doesnt know yet what 
he will say during the brief conversation but he imagines it will 
be rather ordinary chitchat free of political overtones 
i think basically well just say hi what are you doing 
over there what sort of experiments are you working now what do 
you expect to learn hows your food he said during an 
interview friday at johnson space center 
brand wants to converse with the cosmonauts as much as possible 
in russian he was part of the apollosoyuz mission in 1975 in 
which the crews of the american and soviet spacecraft docked in 
space 
parise said he believes communications between the crews were 
handled through ground controllers on that joint mission 
brand is nasas oldest active astronaut 2 weeks shy of his 
59th birthday 
im going to be prepared to do the best i can in russian he 
said ill have to drag out some books im pretty rusty 
parise said its impossible to know when the precedentsetting 
conversation will take place during columbias nineday mission 
since nasa has not yet announced a new launch date 
in addition mir frequently changes orbits making it difficult 
to know when columbias seven astronauts will be able to make 
contact with the two cosmonauts who have been on board the station 
a few months parise said 
columbia originally was scheduled to lift off may 9 with a 100 
million observatory called astro that will measure ultraviolet 
radiation from stars galaxies and quasars but the date was pushed 
back at least a week by the delay in getting discovery off the 
ground with the 15 billion hubble space telescope nasas most 
expensive and complex payload that will orbit 380 miles above earth 
for 15 years 
discovery is scheduled to lift off tuesday two weeks after its 
first launch attempt 
