<TEXT>
horst sindermann a former highranking east 
german communist official and parliament leader has died the 
official adn news agency said he was 74 
sindermann who was ousted from power last year along with the 
hardline government that had ruled for four decades died friday 
from a heart attack adn said quoting family members 
sindermann was a member of the ruling party politburo and 
president of the communistdominated parliament until november 
when mass demonstrations toppled the hardline leadership 
prime minister lothar de maiziere east germanys first freely 
elected leader sent his personal condolences to sindermanns 
widow ingeborg sindermann adn said 
the son of a dresden book printer sindermann was jailed for 
eight months in 1933 for after joining a communist youth group he 
was convicted of high treason in 1935 and spent the next 10 years 
in nazi prison camps until the end of world war ii 
after the victorious allies divided germany into east and west 
sindermann served as editor of various communist party publications 
and held regional party posts until named to the politburo in 1967 
nine years later he became president of parliament and a member 
of the former council of state 
his duties included overseeing the press and radio guarding 
against any softening of the governments hard socialist line 
after the demonstrations that toppled former party leader erich 
honecker the communist leaders who replaced him purged many 
members of the old guard sindermann was stripped of power and 
party membership in november 
an investigation began in january to determine if sindermann 
should be charged with crimes against the country it was abandoned 
a month later because of sindermanns poor health 
a communist caretaker government allowed free elections march 18 
and a government led by noncommunists was elected 
several other fallen leaders are in poor health including the 
78yearold honecker who resides in a sovietrun sanitarium in 
east germany 
a year ago sindermanns death would have warranted a huge state 
funeral the government news agency adn had no information on 
surviving family members or funeral service plans 
</TEXT>
