<TEXT>
mount redoubt exploded saturday morning 
with perhaps its smallest blast to date scientists said but the 
eruption is significant because it is part of an unusually stable 
pattern 
geologist steve brantley with the alaska volcano observatory 
said the eruption at 611 am adt sent steam and ash about 25000 
feet into the air the volcano is about 110 miles southwest of 
anchorage light winds were not expected to carry ash to anchorage 
redoubts recurring stirrings happen about once every six or 
nine days and are regular enough that the observatory now issues 
warnings predicting when the next blast will occur 
its been right or nearly right at least four times since 
december 
saturdays eruption happened just six hours earlier than 
predicted brantley said scientists had set the time window from 
noon saturday to noon tuesday 
mount st helens never exhibited this kind of regular 
eruptive activity brantley said referring to the destructive 
volcano in washington state 
kilauea volcano on the island of hawaii did produce many 
eruptive episodes several dozen that occurred at varying 
intervals he said but there wasnt such a fixed pattern 
lava from kilauea destroyed three houses friday and at least one 
on saturday 
brantley says redoubt does not always give telltale warning 
signs such as heightened earthquakes at its base or discernible 
swelling 
instead scientists are adding up the number of explosions over 
a certain period and basing their predictions on the average number 
of days between explosions 
its interesting that its in this pattern brantley said 
volcanoes do not usually do this 
he said geologists were 70 percent certain that an explosion 
would occur sometime after noon saturday 
redoubt erupted less than 14 hours after a light earthquake 
shook the denali national park area some 300 miles north of the 
volcano 
there were no immediate reports of damage brantley said the two 
geologic events were unrelated 
</TEXT>
