<TEXT>
state attorneys on friday asked a judge to 
prevent a religious sect that believes a nuclear holocaust is 
imminent from occupying a large complex of bomb shelters near 
yellowstone national park 
the department of health and environmental sciences filed a 
complaint in livingston that said continued construction at the 
site could increase the chance of more pollution in the aftermath 
of a 31000gallon fuel spill 
the agency also requested that the church universal and 
triumphant be fined 50000 for allegedly violating state water 
quality laws when the fuel leaked from three underground storage 
tanks at the fallout shelter site near corwin springs 
in addition the state asked that plans for all water and sewage 
systems serving bomb shelters on church property be submitted to 
the department for review 
district judge byron robb took no action on the complaint 
state health officials said earlier they would seek an 
injunction to block further construction on the fallout shelter 
complex which can house about 750 people near corwin springs an 
estimated 30 smaller underground shelters have been built at a 
nearby subdivision 
the bomb shelters reflect the church members belief that 
nuclear war or some other global catastrophe is imminent 
the fuel spills were discovered last week and some of the 
contamination made its way to nearby mol heron creek a pristine 
spawning ground for cutthroat trout additional spills were 
reported last weekend 
earlier this week the department issued an order requiring the 
church to empty and excavate all 35 tanks buried at the mol heron 
site the tanks had a total capacity of 634500 gallons 
fridays complaint seeks a temporary restraining order to block 
further construction on the mol heron shelters and to prevent the 
church from occupying the facilities until the state completes an 
environmental review of the project 
steve pilcher chief of the state water quality bureau has said 
such a review could take six to 12 months 
named as defendants in the complaint were the church elizabeth 
clare prophet church president and spiritual leader ed francis 
her husband and church vice president and several residents of the 
churchowned subdivision of glastonbury 
church spokesman murray steinman said the sect would cooperate 
with the state fully 
