<TEXT>
construction workers erect new buildings 
in this byelorussian village even as residents prepare to flee 
because radiation from the chernobyl accident endangers their lives 
poor organization is wasting millions of rubles one agency 
continues working on construction projects planned before the 
reactor explosion and fire april 26 1986 while others evacuate 
residents of the same village 
criticism of how the disaster was handled began early the 
government came under attack at home and abroad because the 
accident was not reported for two days after the reactor had sent 
up a huge cloud of radiation that eventually worked its way around 
the world 
politicians elected under more liberal policies introduced since 
1986 say full information about radiation levels and health 
problems was kept secret 
the government lifted secrecy restrictions on such information 
last year as politicians learned more they pressed for and won 
evacuations of some of the estimated 4 million people still living 
on irradiated land 
byelorussian writer ales adamovich said the alleged coverup and 
official claims that no radiation sickness was diagnosed in 
