<TEXT>
gene young is 39 and a professor at 
jackson state university but give him an instant and he is 19 
again a student on the same campus and gripped by fear 
he hears again repeated rifle blasts shattering the 
shirtsleevemild night air he remembers the screaming and crying 
he can see the broken glass and the blood 
and young remembers first word that a jackson state college 
student had been killed as police in riot gear fired on a cluster 
of students gathered in front of a womens dormitory to protest the 
vietnam war and the deaths 10 days earlier of four kent state 
university students 
a high school student who was crossing the campus was also 
fatally wounded 
classes were dismissed commencement was canceled and most 
students left for home but young a jackson native stayed on the 
innercity campus several days i felt something had to be 
done he recalled in an interview 
what young did was convince city high school students they 
should boycott classes until after phillip l gibbs 21 and james 
earl green 17 were buried 
young said he is still trying to figure out what happened 
to this day i dont know what could have precipitated that 
kind of violence said young a professor of speech and dramatic 
arts 
the night of may 14 1970 was the third in a row of campus 
demonstrations and offcampus disturbances at mostly black jackson 
state students were agitated and upset about the shootings at kent 
state which occurred when national guardsmen fired on a crowd of 
antiwar demonstrators 
students also were fed up with the racial epithets shouted from 
cars by white west jackson residents who drove straight through the 
jackson state campus on busy lynch street to reach downtown 
the atmosphere was very charged recalled john a peoples 
jr president of jackson state from 1967 to 1984 but i had 
from the very beginning given the students a lot of freedom 
he and young blamed racial intolerance for the shootings the 
citys and states white officials never wanted black students to 
demonstrate peoples asserted 
young concurred mississippi went to a great extent to show 
how they would keep niggers in line if they were disorderly he 
said 
young also believes the jackson state shootings would largely 
have been ignored if not for what happened at kent state 
we know the history of blacks being victimized by whites in 
mississippi he said had the incident not occurred a week 
after kent state it would have been all but forgotten 
over the years that has been borne out people remember kent 
state but they dont remember jackson state 
the night gibbs and green were killed 22 police officers in 
full riot gear advanced on the students milling outside the 
alexander residence center some reports counted 75 to 100 students 
in front of the dormitory police said the number was closer to 400 
a voice on a bullhorn ordered students to disperse then the 
shooting began 
in 25 seconds gibbs and green were killed and seven others had 
been wounded an fbi report counted 275 holes in the west wing of 
yellowbrick alexander hall 21 were believed caused by automatic 
weapons 250 or more by shotgun buckshot every window on the 
street side of the fivestory building was blown out 
their intent was not just to disperse the crowd but to bring 
death and destruction young said it amazes me that no more 
people were killed 
that nights demonstrations had begun after students were drawn 
outside to watch firefighters douse a burning dump truck on an 
adjacent street 
city and state officers were called to the scene after 
firefighters were pelted with rocks and bottles thrown some say 
by neighborhood residents 
whatever the students started the corner boys took up 
peoples said at night you couldnt tell the corner boys from 
the students 
officers claimed they opened fire after a sniper shot from a 
dormitory window and a highway patrol officer was hit by an object 
thrown from the crowd 
to that young commented the elusive sniper always amazes me 
how he gets around the world 
and students suggested at the time that what police took to be a 
gunshot might have been the sound of a soft drink bottle smashing 
on a sidewalk after it was dropped from a dorm window by a student 
who saw the advancing officers 
families of the dead and injured sued the city of jackson and 
the state of mississippi but a federal appeals court ruled in 1974 
that damages could not be awarded because it was impossible to 
determine who was to blame 
however the court did say that the barrage of gunfire far 
exceeded the response that was appropriate 
the presidents commission on campus unrest said police had 
fired blindly into the students and no evidence was found of any 
sniper the commission said the blame lay jointly with public 
officials students and college administratiors 
i didnt think anyone would be punished for it in the first 
place nureen gibbs ray sister of phillip gibbs said from her 
home in ripley they said there was an investigation but i dont 
think there was ever anything concrete 
gibbs was a junior prelaw student he had a pregnant wife and 
child back home in ripley his wife has since remarried changed 
her childrens last name and lives in arizona 
green was a track star at jim hill high school he was crossing 
the jackson campus after getting off work 
ray said gibbs had called her that night to let her know about 
the disturbances on campus but said he and their sister mary also 
a jackson state student would be leaving for home soon the 
siblings parents both were dead 
his car already was packed he had gone up to get our sister 
because they were coming home ray said 
mary she said lives in chicago and doesnt like to talk about 
that night 
dr roland colom a columbus dentist attended junior high with 
gibbs and was his roomate at jackson state it was really strange 
for me to hear that he was out there amid the demonstrators 
because i was out there the night before and tried to get him to go 
out and he wouldnt colom said 
jackson state has grown from 3700 students in 1970 to more than 
7150 today 93 percent of them black lynch street the 
