<TEXT>
when a federal judge seized eastern airlines and 
appointed an outsider to run it he did something unusual in 
modernday bankruptcies but quite common before the law was 
overhauled 12 years ago 
the action by judge burton lifland this past week surprised many 
bankruptcy attorneys and led some to speculate that these outside 
managers known as trustees would be appointed in more bankruptcy 
reorganizations 
liflands order also amounted to a rebuke for easterns parent 
company texas air corp and its chairman frank lorenzo who have 
contended that they alone could salvage eastern from death 
the judge departed from a principle enshrined in a 1978 reform 
of the federal bankruptcy code known as debtorinpossession it 
takes for granted that the best managers for ailing companies are 
the existing managers 
the reform says only in rare circumstances such as substantial 
evidence of fraud or incompetence by management should trustees 
replace the people who supposedly know the most about the business 
theyre trying to save 
the presumption is that the debtor in possession will stay in 
place and manage the business said richard gitlin a hartford 
conn bankruptcy attorney and past president of the american 
bankruptcy institute i think the fact a trustee has been 
appointed in the eastern case is very significant 
by contrast in earlier bankruptcy law the presumption was that 
the companies got into trouble partly because management didnt 
know what it was doing and should be booted out 
prior to the reform a trustee was appointed in every big 
case said frank kennedy a retired university of michigan law 
professor and bankruptcy expert who played a major role in the 1978 
overhaul passed by congress 
part of the reason for the reform stemmed from the inability of 
many trustees to operate the failing businesses they were entrusted 
with salvaging under the old system many trustees often were 
political appointees who in many instances used their position for 
personal gain 
they would take a business not understand the steps to take 
in order to revitalize them have an agenda to generate business 
for themselves and many if not most of the businesses failed as a 
result said neal d colton a bankruptcy attorney with dechert 
price amp roads a philadelphia law firm 
in some respects thats the implication in liflands decision 
to take eastern away from lorenzo and texas and appoint veteran 
airline manager martin r shugrue to run it instead 
eastern has racked up enormous losses since a strike in march 
1989 that stemmed in large part from union hatred of lorenzo 
management eastern says the strike drove the carrier into chapter 
11 bankruptcy proceedings 
since then the management has hired replacement workers 
reorganized eastern into a smaller airline and repeatedly revised 
downward the amount of money it planned to repay unsecured 
creditors who are owed nearly 1 billion creditor willingness to 
trust management turned to impatience and exasperation evidence 
also surfaced that texas air had deliberately transferred eastern 
assets away to sister nonunion carrier continental airlines 
hurting easterns ability to survive this was one of the 
accusations made by the unions in their decision to strike 
lifland emphasized what he called managements inability to make 
reliable business forecasts as part of the basis for his decision 
he also said texas airs treatment of eastern suggested parental 
neglect 
kennedy said in the eastern case the court considered the 
balance of equities and decided that in light of the unseemly 
history of eastern its inability to deal with problems to the 
satisfaction of unsecured creditors it was time to get an 
independent trustee in there 
some bankruptcy trustee experts suggested lifland waited much 
too long to resolve what they called an intense unionmanagement 
conflict in the eastern case that was central to the airlines 
problems 
this was very apparent in the eastern bankruptcy deals that 
could have been worked were impossible said gary knostman 
president of the national association of bankruptcy trustees and a 
professional trustee himself 
a trustee isnt fighting the personalty battles and can 
normally get cooperation among groups much quicker he said 
im not criticizing lorenzos management but lets face it he 
was not a popular subject with the mechanics and pilots you get 
that bad blood its hard to make deals work 
in other business and economic news this past week 
former junk bond financier michael milken perhaps the 
bestknown figure of the 1980s era of easy money and wall street 
excess reached agreement with federal prosecutors to plead guilty 
in connection with securities fraud charges sources said milken 
who had insisted he was innocent for more than two years was 
expected to pay 600 million in fines and face a prison term 
a financial squeeze on banks appeared increasingly evident 
because of souring real estate and third world loans citicorp the 
nations largest bank reported a large loss and its creditrating 
faced review several other banks also reported losses or lower 
profits and federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said a 
majority of banks have tightened lending practices 
the trade deficit shrank in february to 649 billion the 
smallest gap in more than six years but the drop reported by the 
government was largely due to a decline in imports and private 
economists suggested it did not signal an increased foreign 
appetite for us goods considered crucial to longterm 
improvement in the us trade balance 
