<TEXT>
the plea bargain agreement by indicted financier 
michael milken marks another stunning chapter in wall streets 
financial scandals which saw the fall of both the junk bond genius 
and the empire he created 
after a year of maintaining his innocence milken agreed friday 
to plead guilty to six felonies and pay 600 million in penalties 
to settle government charges in the largest individual securities 
fraud case in history 
the former head of drexel burnham lambert incs highyield bond 
department who parlayed the risky securities into a 
multibilliondollar business and two others had been named in a 
sweeping federal fraud and racketeering indictment stemming from 
the confessions of speculator ivan boesky 
boesky who cooperated with the government in settling charges 
that he ran a stock trading network based on illegal insider 
information fingered milken and drexel as key participants in his 
schemes 
milken repeatedly said he would be vindicated at trial but 
after lengthy negotiations between prosecutors and his attorneys 
he agreed to the plea bargain 
its a big victory to get a plea to six felonies said alan 
bromberg a securities law professor at southern methodist 
university who has followed the milken case closely its 
certainly one up for the government over wall street 
for both sides the deal also removes the risk and cost of the 
lengthy jury trial that was expected over the charges 
milken is expected to enter the guilty plea to the felony counts 
and agree to pay fines and restitution next week in us district 
court in manhattan said individuals close to the case who asked 
not to be named 
the sources cautioned that while a settlement had been reached 
it would not be final until the plea formally is entered 
milken his brother lowell and former drexel trader bruce 
newberg were indicted last year on 98 counts of fraud and 
racketeering related to insider trading and other alleged 
securities violations in a series of takeover deals from 1985 to 
1987 
none of the counts in the plea bargain relates to insider 
trading and there is no racketeering charge as part of the deal 
the government agreed to drop all charges against lowell milken 
the sources said 
assistant us attorney john k carroll declined to comment on 
the deal a spokesman for milken also declined to comment 
it was unclear whether the government would recommend a specific 
sentence to us district judge kimba wood milken would face a 
maximum of up to 30 years in prison on the six felony counts a 
single racketeering count would have carried a 20year sentence 
but the government could recommend that milken serve the counts 
concurrently for a maximum term of five years in prison 
it also was unclear whether milken would be forced to cooperate 
with any further government investigations 
the deal would settle separate civil charges brought by the 
securities and exchange commission in 1988 the sources said the 
600 million in penalties would be split between criminal fines and 
a fund for payment of any civil lawsuits related to milkens 
activities 
milken 43 is widely acknowledged as one of the most important 
financial figures of the 1980s 
milken is credited with reshaping corporate america by 
pioneering the widespread use of highyield bonds which offer high 
interest payments to compensate for the risky nature of the 
companies that issue them 
the socalled junk bonds were used to finance growth for 
hundreds of companies and fed a wave of hostile corporate takeovers 
in the 1980s 
milken was paid handsomely for his work receiving 1 billion 
from 198387 including 550 million in 1987 alone 
but drexel collapsed in february partly due to the longranging 
impact of its decision to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a 
record 650 million to settle its own case 
the milken settlement marks a complete change of course he had 
pleaded innocent to the original charges and had said he would take 
the case to trial 
since handing up the march 1989 indictment the government 
repeatedly delayed a promised superseding indictment 
the new charges were said to include allegations separate from 
information provided by boesky to strengthen the case boesky who 
pleaded guilty to a single felony count in november 1986 and paid a 
100 million fine was considered an easy target for defense 
lawyers 
drexels own plea bargain allowed it to avoid a racketeering 
indictment that could have put the firm out of business 
but the brokerage which grew from a secondtier player to a 
powerhouse on wall street largely because of milkens prowess 
never recovered from its plea deal and the sharp decline of the 
junk bond market beginning last fall it has been liquidating since 
filing for bankruptcy court protection in february 
drexel was forced to sever ties with milken under terms of its 
sec settlement milken resigned from drexel last june to set up his 
own consulting and investing firm 
</TEXT>
