<TEXT>
when michael milken pleaded innocent to 98 
counts of fraud and racketeering a y release sunday ear ago supporters 
donned caps 
reading mike milken we believe in you and cheered wildly as he 
exited manhattan federal court 
milken always has believed in himself so his decision to 
reverse course plead guilty to six felonies and pay 600 million 
in penalties was a stunning event 
the move reflected the governments power and the pressure of 
more than three years at the center of wall streets scandal 
there was no end in sight a friend of milkens said after 
the plea deal was revealed the physical and the emotional toll 
was just spectacular 
milken in many ways was the damocles of wall street creating 
and then ruling the junk bond market that drove the boom years of 
the 1980s bu the outcome leaves many issues 
unresolved milkens and many other wall street fraud cases relied 
on gray areas of the law plea bargains leave legal matters no 
clearer 
we never had a full development of the facts and we never had 
a court ruling that of these things were illegal bromberg said 
all we have is somebody saying i give up 
all that is very unsatisfying in wanting to know what really 
happened and what the law is on all these points he said 
milken the californiabred son of an accountant parlayed a 
novel idea about an obscure kind of debt into the gear that turned 
american finance in the 1980s his work made him the highest paid 
man in one year in american history 550 million in 1987 
milken has said he would rather be remembered for helping 
companies that needed financing unavailable from conventional 
sources such as commercial banks or the highgrade corporate debt 
market and for his extensive charitable activities 
but in all likelihood history will remember milken more for his 
legal travails that focused on allegations of widespread insider 
trading and other fraudulent activity 
milkens plea bargain does not include any counts related to 
insider trading and likely will not even involve any junkbond 
financed deals people familiar with the deal said it also would 
preclude any further investigations of milken associates 
milken helped create wall streets phenomenal growth in the last 
decade receiving a notoriety he never sought before becoming the 
target of the largest financial investigation in history 
born on the fourth of july in 1946 milken grew up in encino 
calif as a boy he helped his father prepare tax returns for 
clients 
milken graduated from the university of california at berkeley 
majoring in business administration and married his highschool 
sweetheart lori anne hackel he went on to the university of 
pennsylvanias wharton school 
as an undergraduate milken was influenced by a study published 
in the 1950s by an academician named w braddock hickman the study 
postulated that a diversified investment portfolio of highinterest 
bonds of risky companies with low credit ratings could be 
profitable because returns would amply make up for defaults 
milken applied the theory when he was hired fulltime by drexels 
bondtrading department in 1970 after working in its philadelphia 
office during business school 
a rapid success milken generated sizable profits for the firm 
through his highyield bond trading and drexel gradually gave him 
wide independence in 1978 the firm allowed milken to move the 
highyield bond department to beverly hills calif 
drexel used junk bonds to finance hundreds of small companies in 
the 1980s reaping hundreds of millions of dollars in fees milken 
controlled an empire of buyers and sellers of the securities issued 
by the wall street firm 
but junk bonds also were used by several flamboyant corporate 
raiders to mount hostile takeovers that drew fire from legislators 
and big business as a threat to corporate america milken was the 
lightning rod for that criticism 
after being linked in the press in late 1986 to boeskys illegal 
stock trading network milken and drexel became the main targets of 
the government innvestigators 
they were charged with civil fraud and other allegations by the 
securities and exchange commission in 1988 drexel that winter 
agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay 650 million in 
penalties 
milken was indicted the following march along with his brother 
and former drexel trader bruce newberg he resigned from drexel in 
june and set up a consulting and investing firm that advises 
companies but does not issue securities 
while milken maintained his innocence he indicated in an 
interview last fall that he just wanted the ordeal to end 
if you spent your whole life trying to build things some of 
these things sap your energy and you feel frustrated he said 
</TEXT>
